ithub.com/users/coderabbitai%5Bbot%5D/received_events","type":"Bot","user_view_type":"public","site_admin":false},"body":"_Г”ГңГЎВҙВ©Г… Potential issue_ | _ВӯЖ’Ж’ГЎ Major_ | _Г”ГңГӯ Quick win_\n\n<details>\n<summary>ВӯЖ’ВәВ® Analysis chain</summary>\n\nВӯЖ’Г…Гј Script executed:\n\n```shell\n#!/bin/bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\nfile=\".github/workflows/epic6-testing.yml\"\necho \"==> File: $file\"\nwc -l \"$file\"\n# Show the relevant region around the referenced lines\nnl -ba \"$file\" | sed -n '70,140p'\n\n# Show any nearby lock/audit logic in the workflow\necho \"==> All 'Lock-Free Audit' occurrences:\"\nrg -n \"Lock-Free Audit|Select-String.*lock|lock\\\\s*\\\\(\" \"$file\" || true\n```\n\nRepository: mdasdispatch-hash/universal-or-strategy\n\nLength of output: 230\n\n---\n\nВӯЖ’Г®Гү Web query:\n\n`PowerShell Select-String -SimpleMatch behavior regex vs literal`\n\nВӯЖ’ГҶГӯ Result:\n\nIn PowerShell, Select-StringГ”ГҮГ–s -SimpleMatch makes the -Pattern treated as a literal text substring (no regular-expression interpretation), unlike the default behavior where -Pattern is a regular expression. 1) Default (regex) By default, Select-String interprets the Pattern parameter as a regular expression.[1] So regex metacharacters in your Pattern (for example., *, [], etc.) are processed as regex syntax (unless you escape them).\n\nCitations:\n\n- 1: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.utility/select-string?view=powershell-7.4\n\n---\n\nВӯЖ’Г®Гү Web query:\n\n`PowerShell Select-String -Path wildcard support for src/**/*.cs (does ** recursive wildcard work)`\n\nВӯЖ’ГҶГӯ Result:\n\nIn PowerShell, Select-StringГ”ГҮГ–s -Path parameter allows wildcards (it Г”ГҮВЈsupports wildcards: TrueГ”ГҮГҳ), but it does not document support for Г”ГҮВЈglobstarГ”ГҮГҳ/recursive wildcard syntax like (double-asterisk) in a single path pattern. Select-String examples show using * and performing recursion via Get-ChildItem -Recurse (or by piping Get-ChildItem output to Select-String), not via a pattern in -Path.[1][2] So for your example src//*.cs: - */*.cs style single-level wildcards are supported as part of the -Path wildcard matching.[1] - / recursive matching is not documented as supported for Select-String -Path, and you should not rely on it working. Recommended reliable approach (works for any depth): Get-ChildItem -Path 'src' -Filter '*.cs' -Recurse | Select-String -Pattern '<your text>' If you must use Select-String with only -Path (no pipe), use a pattern that doesnГ”ГҮГ–t require recursive directory matching (for example, a single directory level like src/*.cs), because Select-StringГ”ГҮГ–s recursion isnГ”ГҮГ–t shown via patterns.[1][2]\n\nCitations:\n\n- 1: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.utility/select-string?view=powershell-7.6\n- 2: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.utility/select-string?view=powershell-7.4\n\n---\n\nВӯЖ’Г…Гј Script executed:\n\n```shell\n#!/bin/bash\nset -euo pipefail\nfile=\".github/workflows/epic6-testing.yml\"\necho \"==> File: $file\"\nwc -l \"$file\"\n\necho \"==> Lines 90-130 (with line numbers via awk)\"\nawk 'NR>=90 && NR<=130 {printf \"%5d %s\\n\", NR, $0}' \"$file\"\n\necho \"==> Find any Select-String lock audit in the workflow\"\nrg -n \"Lock-Free Audit|Select-String|lock\\\\s*\\\\(\" \"$file\" || true\n\nif [ -d \"src\" ]; then\n  echo \"==> Count of *.cs files under src/\"\n  find src -type f -name '*.cs' | wc -l\n  echo \"==> Count of *.cs files directly under src/ (non-recursive)\"\n  find src -maxdepth 1 -type f -name '*.cs' | wc -l\n  echo \"==> Example subdir *.cs paths (top 20)\"\n  find src -type f -name '*.cs' | awk 'NR<=20{print}' \nelse\n  echo \"==> No src/ directory found at repo root\"\nfi\n```\n\nRepository: mdasdispatch-hash/universal-or-strategy\n\nLength of output: 2534\n\n---\n\nВӯЖ’Г…Гј Script executed:\n\n```shell\n#!/bin/bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\n# Search for lock usage in C# sources\necho \"==> rg for lock(\"\nrg -n --glob '*.cs' \"lock\\s*\\(\" src | head -n 50 || true\n\necho \"==> rg for literal 'lock\\\\s*\\\\(' (what SimpleMatch would look for)\"\nrg -n --glob '*.cs' \"lock\\\\\\\\s\\*\\\\\\\\\\(\" src || true\n\necho \"==> any C# outside src/?\"\n# (If there are none, then the audit scope issue is less important.)\nfind . -type f -name '*.cs' | sed 's|^\\./||' | head -n 50\necho \"==> total .cs files outside src/:\"\nfind . -type f -name '*.cs' | awk '{print $0}' | grep -v '^./src/' | wc -l\n```\n\nRepository: mdasdispatch-hash/universal-or-strategy\n\nLength of output: 3139\n\n---\n\nВӯЖ’Г®Гү Web query:\n\n`Does .NET regex support POSIX character classes like [[:space:]] inside character brackets?`\n\nВӯЖ’ГҶГӯ Result:\n\nYes. In.NET regular expressions, POSIX character classes of the form [[:space:]] are supported inside character brackets. For example, you can use a bracket expression like `[[:space:]]` and it matches whitespace characters. MicrosoftГ”ГҮГ–s.NET regular expression documentation lists the supported character-class constructs (including whitespace via `\\s`), and.NETГ”ГҮГ–s regex language includes support for bracketed character-group forms (i.e., `[...]` character classes) that can contain POSIX bracket expressions like `[[:space:]]`. If what you want is whitespace,.NET also supports the shorthand `\\s` (equivalent to whitespace), which is often simpler than the POSIX spelling. For instance, `\\s` matches whitespace characters [1].\n\nCitations:\n\n- 1: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/base-types/character-classes-in-regular-expressions\n\n---\n\nВӯЖ’Г…Гј Script executed:\n\n```shell\n#!/bin/bash\nset -euo pipefail\n\necho \"==> .github/workflows/epic6-testing.yml lock audit snippet context\"\nawk 'NR>=95 && NR<=115 {print NR \":\" $0}' .github/workflows/epic6-testing.yml\n\necho \"==> Does src/ contain any .cs files in subdirectories (depth>=2)?\"\nfind src -mindepth 2 -type f -name '*.cs' | wc -l\n